node.text:
Finally was able to capture some good footage of some of the most famous locals here in Tofo, Mozambique. All of a sudden we saw a massive whale shark during our diving interval. 🦈 We quickly jumped off the boat only to find it charging straight at me. The whale shark holds many records for size in the animal kingdom, most notably being by far the largest living nonmammalian vertebrate. They can grow up to 20m or 60 feet! 😱

node.text:
The other day we where lucky enough to spot a leopard shark just chilling in the sand 🦈 (also know in some areas as a zebra shark). If you listen closely you can hear some hear humpback whales singing in the distance. Hearing those whales sing while diving here in Tofo (Mozambique) has added a whole other dimension to spending time underwater. Definitely check out @liquiddiveadventures . Diving here with the mega fauna and those whale sounds on the background has been an absolute dream. 

All sharks are glorious animals in their own way unfortunately they have a negative connotation in our society. Despite the fact that they are one of the most import animals to maintain structure in healthy ocean ecosystems. Because they are at the top of the food chain, they help to keep a healthy between all animals and marine flora further down the chain.

node.text:
A few days ago we were fortunate enough to spot one of the most endangered seaturtles, the hawksbill turtle (critically endangered). They’re among the least abundant sea turtles, with an estimated population of fewer than 8,000 nesting females across their range in the tropics.

According to a new study, which drew on data from the Atlantic, Pacific, and Indian Oceans, nearly nine million hawksbills were hunted for their shells during the 148-year period from 1844 to 1992. 😞

node.text:
Despite being the world’s largest oceanic stingray, it is very rarely spotted alive, and almost nothing is known about it. Before the early 2000s, there were only a couple verified live sightings of smalleye stingrays, and here in Tofo, Mozambique is probably the only place left in the world where you still have a small chance of seeing them. This probably also the first time a mama and her baby were captured on video. One of the reasons there probably only a few thousand left is the fact they only produce one offspring every few years. That’s why I was so excited that I was able to capture this precious moment.

Leopard Muray eels can grow up to 3m (9 feet) this one is probably somewhere in between. Adults are notorious for possibly being aggressive and there are a few instances know where scuba divers where attacked by them. Most of them consisted of incidents where the diver got too close to them and they kinda like their privacy that’s why you’ll mostly find them in small caves. 

I haven’t been able to post as much as I would love to as the internet here in Africa is not always the best. But also because I am doing my divemaster here which may required a bit more studying and practical tests than I expected. Nevertheless this place has been amazing so far, if you’re looking for a diving vacation, Tofo (Mozambique) is the place to be! Big shoutout to @liquiddiveadventures for hosting me!

node.text:
Finally my first (short) clip from Mozambique! So far everything has been amazing here, we go diving almost every day and I couldn’t image a better spot to do my divemaster (@liquiddiveadventures). I still have a lot to learn not only for my divemaster course but about editing & color grading these videos but I’d like to think that this one turned out pretty nice.

The peacock mantis shrimp has always been one of my favourite animals in the underwater world as it posses some superman-like abilities. It can strike its appendages (“fists”) quicker than a .22 caliber bullet that has just been fired. At those speeds, the water surrounding them briefly reaches the temperature of the sun. Isn’t the underwater world just full of wonders?

node.text:
Although basking sharks are the second biggest fish in the sea, they have tiny prey, zooplankton. After locating a zooplankton patch, they open their giant mouths and swim through it, as shown in this video by @bertiegregory. The huge white gill arches contain rakers—structures that snag plankton from the water that passes through the mouth. Unlike many other species of filter feeders that are able to pump water past these gill rakers, basking sharks feed passively. This means they must swim to eat. Given their huge size, they need to do a lot of eating—and therefore a lot of swimming. It’s estimated they can filter two million liters of water an hour! Concerned about being swallowed by these gentle giants? While they have a three-foot-wide mouth, their throats are incredibly narrow, so even if they wanted to swallow a person (which they don’t), they physically couldn’t!

Video credits to @bertiegregory via @natgeo

The Octopus Cyanea can produce a variety of color patterns and elaborate skin textures that resemble the ocean floor — because they hunt during the day, their ability to change colors is exceptionally fast. ⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
🔍🐙 You can ID this species by looking at the dark oval false eyespots with no iridescent ring. Also— you see those spots that appear down their arms? Look for these two things on our next story quiz!⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
One day octopus was observed changing patterns 1,000 times over a 7 hour period of time- this species definitely puts on a show! 😍🐙⁣⁣⁣⁣

Follow @ocean.explorer_ for more interesting facts! 🌊🤙🏻
